mallest possible magnitudes: the interpolation is bandlimited. Second, if the formula_39 are real numbers, then formula_106 is real as well.\nIn contrast, the most obvious trigonometric interpolation polynomial is the one in which the frequencies range from 0 to formula_107 (instead of roughly formula_108 to formula_109 as above), similar to the inverse DFT formula. This interpolation does \"not\" minimize the slope, and is \"not\" generally real-valued for real formula_39; its use is a common mistake.\nThe unitary DFT.\nAnother way of looking at the DFT is to note that in the above discussion, the DFT can be expressed as the DFT matrix, a Vandermonde matrix,\n in 1867,\nformula_111\nwhere formula_112 is a primitive \"N\"th root of unity.\nFor example, in the case when formula_113, formula_114, and\nformula_115\n(which is a Hadamard matrix) or when formula_28 as in the above, formula_117, and\nformula_118\nThe inverse transform is then given by the inverse of the above matrix,\nformula_119\nWith unitary normalization constants formula_120, the DFT becomes a unitary transformation, defined by a unitary matrix:\nformula_121\nwhere formula_122 is the determinant function. The determinant is the product of the eigenvalues, which are always formula_123 or formula_124 as described below. In a real vector space, a unitary transformation can be thought of as simply a rigid rotation of the coordinate system, and all of the properties of a rigid rotation can be found in the unitary DFT.\nThe orthogonality of the DFT is now expressed as an orthonormality condition (which arises in many areas of mathematics as described in root of unity):\nformula_125\nIf X is defined as the unitary DFT of the vector x, then\nformula_126\nand the Parseval's theorem is expressed as\nformula_127\nIf we view the DFT as just a coordinate transformation which simply specifies the components of a vector in a new coordinate system, then the above is just the statement that the dot product of two vecto