hich is also involutory.\nEigenvalues and eigenvectors.\nThe eigenvalues of the DFT matrix are simple and well-known, whereas the eigenvectors are complicated, not unique, and are the subject of ongoing research. Explicit formulas are given with a significant amount of number theory.\nConsider the unitary form formula_150 defined above for the DFT of length \"N\", where\nformula_151\nThis matrix satisfies the matrix polynomial equation:\nformula_152\nThis can be seen from the inverse properties above: operating formula_150 twice gives the original data in reverse order, so operating formula_150 four times gives back the original data and is thus the identity matrix. This means that the eigenvalues formula_155 satisfy the equation:\nformula_156\nTherefore, the eigenvalues of formula_150 are the fourth roots of unity: formula_155 is +1, \u22121, +\"i\", or \u2212\"i\".\nSince there are only four distinct eigenvalues for this formula_159 matrix, they have some multiplicity. The multiplicity gives the number of linearly independent eigenvectors corresponding to each eigenvalue. (There are \"N\" independent eigenvectors; a unitary matrix is never defective.)\nThe problem of their multiplicity was solved by McClellan and Parks (1972), although it was later shown to have been equivalent to a problem solved by Gauss (Dickinson and Steiglitz, 1982). The multiplicity depends on the value of \"N\" modulo 4, and is given by the following table:\nOtherwise stated, the characteristic polynomial of formula_150 is:\nformula_161\nNo simple analytical formula for general eigenvectors is known. Moreover, the eigenvectors are not unique because any linear combination of eigenvectors for the same eigenvalue is also an eigenvector for that eigenvalue. Various researchers have proposed different choices of eigenvectors, selected to satisfy useful properties like orthogonality and to have \"simple\" forms (e.g., McClellan and Parks, 1972; Dickinson and Steiglitz, 1982; Gr\u00fcnbaum, 1982; Candan \"et al.\", 2000; Hanna \"et al.\", 2004; Gurevich and Hadani, 2008).\nOne method to construct DFT eigenvectors to an eigenvalue formula_155 is based on the linear combination of operators:\nformula_163\nFor an arbitrary vector formula_164, vector formula_165 satisfies:\nformula_166\nhence, vector formula_167 is, indeed, the eigenvector of DFT matrix formula_150. Operators formula_169 project vectors onto subspaces which are orthogonal for each value of formula_155. That is, for two eigenvectors, formula_165 and formula_172 we have:\nformula_173\nHowever, in general, projection operator method does not produce orthogonal eigenvectors within one subspace. The operator formula_174 can be seen as a matrix, whose columns are eigenvectors of formula_150, but they are not orthogonal. When a set of vectors formula_176, spanning formula_177-dimensional space (where formula_177 is the multiplicity of eigenvalue formula_155) is chosen to generate the set of eigenvectors formula_180 to eigenvalue formula_155, the mutual orthogonality of formula_182 is not guaranteed. However, the orthogonal set can be obtained by further applying orthogonalization algorithm to the set formula_183, e.g. Gram-Schmidt process.\nA straightforward approach to obtain DFT eigenvectors is to discretize an eigenfunction of the continuous Fourier transform, of which the most famous is the Gaussian function. Since periodic summation of the function means discretizing its frequency spectrum and discretization means periodic summation of the spectrum, the discretized and periodically summed Gaussian function yields an eigenvector of the discrete transform:\nThe closed form expression for the series can be expressed by Jacobi theta functions as\nSeveral other simple closed-form analytical eigenvectors for special DFT period \"N\" were found (Casper-Yakimov, 2024):\nFor DFT period \"N\" = 2\"L\" + 1 = 4\"K\" + 1, where \"K\" is an integer, the following is an eigenvector of DFT:\nFor DFT period \"N\"